<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12115j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12115j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12115j"> 115(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> prendre la part du feu</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">L&apos;abb&eacute; de Luxeuil leur promettait de se tenir en repos sur cet irritant probl&egrave;me; pensant &agrave; juste titre ne pouvoir pas obtenir de lui davantage, ils firent <mark>la part du feu</i> et n&apos;insist&egrave;rent plus. <br><font color="green">[The abbot of Luxeuil promised them he would keep quiet about this irritating problem; justly concluding that they could not get anything more out of him, they took the realistic course of insisting no longer.]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 91</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The French idiom inaccurately noted by Joyce, <i>faire la part du feu</i> (to take the fire into account), derives from fire-fighting and means to destroy an area to prevent fire from spreading, or to abandon (to a fire) what could not be saved anyway; to make a realistic assesment of a situation in order to concentrate on what is essential.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c12119b" href="c12all.htm#c12119b">VI.C.12:119(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
